The findings from the study , commissioned by relationship website eHarmony , show that despite needing around 20 hours of mental down-time a week to feel relaxed and refreshed , less than two in five Britons -LRB- 39 per cent -RRB- are meeting the requirement .

Among those who said they do n't have enough me time , more than a third -LRB- 36 per cent -RRB- felt more tired , while others felt more stressed -LRB- 33 per cent -RRB- , burnt out -LRB- 22 per cent -RRB- , and even depressed -LRB- 14 per cent -RRB- . One in 25 -LRB- four per cent -RRB- even said they feel less attractive .

More than one in seven people -LRB- 15 per cent -RRB- say they have no me time at all , while one in nine -LRB- 11 per cent -RRB- have less than five hours a week .

Longer working hours is one of the biggest drains on taking time out , with 42 per cent saying their job gets in the way of their relaxation , rising to 57 per cent among those aged 45 to 54 .

For younger adults , browsing social media sites has a big impact , with 10 per cent citing ` FOMO ' - fear of missing out - as a real issue .

Other time drains include household chores -LRB- 41 per cent -RRB- , personal admin -LRB- 21 per cent -RRB- and thinking about work -LRB- 18 per cent -RRB- , while even optional activities , such as group hobbies -LRB- 14 per cent -RRB- , can have a negative impact .

